td.content: John Smith, a 72-year-old male with a history of hyperlipidemia and prediabetes, presented for a routine follow-up. His lipid levels remained well-controlled on atorvastatin 40 mg daily, with no significant side effects. The patient was advised to continue his current medications and schedule a follow-up in one year for routine labs and reassessment. No acute issues noted at this visit.

During this annual follow-up, the patient was monitored for hyperlipidemia and prediabetes. John Smith's LDL cholesterol levels were improved, and his fasting glucose was monitored. No acute symptoms of heart failure, though monitoring was recommended due to borderline renal function. Lifestyle counseling continued to address prediabetes and weight management.

John Smith returned for his annual check-up, with increased fatigue noted during physical activity. Blood pressure was stable, but a rise in creatinine suggested declining kidney function. A referral to a nephrologist was considered to assess renal insufficiency. The patient was advised to monitor his weight and report any signs of swelling or increasing fatigue, which could indicate worsening heart failure.

tr.td: Outpatient - Cardiology visit for worsening shortness of breath

td.content: John Smith presented with complaints of worsening shortness of breath and weight gain of 25 pounds over the past year. Physical exam revealed +2 pitting edema, irregular heart sounds, and lab results showed elevated proBNP and worsening renal function. Diuretic therapy was intensified, and a follow-up echocardiogram was ordered. Patient was counseled on adherence to a low-sodium diet, weight monitoring, and recognizing early signs of fluid retention.

tr.td: Hospitalization - Decompensated heart failure with reduced ejection fraction

td.content: John Smith was admitted for decompensated heart failure, presenting with severe shortness of breath, orthopnea, and peripheral edema. An echocardiogram confirmed a reduced ejection fraction of 30%. IV furosemide was administered to manage fluid overload. During the hospitalization, it was noted that the patient was overdue for a colonoscopy. His last colonoscopy in 2016 revealed multiple polyps, and he was advised to return for a follow-up in 3 years, but this was missed. Discharge instructions included a recommendation to schedule this overdue screening, along with management of heart failure. He was discharged with instructions to monitor his weight and blood pressure, adhere to a low-sodium diet, and follow up with both his cardiologist and gastroenterologist.

tr.td: Echocardiogram - Assessment of left ventricular function
Cardiology Imaging Center, 456 Maple Lane, Lakeside, NJ 07047

td.content: John Smith underwent an echocardiogram to assess his heart function due to worsening symptoms of heart failure. The echocardiogram revealed an ejection fraction of 35%, with mild dilation of the left ventricle and hypokinesis of the inferior and posterior walls. There were mild mitral and tricuspid regurgitations noted. The patient was advised to continue his current heart failure medications and to monitor for any signs of further symptom worsening. A follow-up visit with the cardiologist was scheduled to discuss the echocardiogram results and adjust his treatment plan if necessary.
